Functional API implementation of MobileNetV2 Transfer Learning to recognize Alpaca images

Author: Aditya Patel

Beauty of MobileNet is I can feed larger image than what mobilenet was originally trained on. By feeding 512 x 512 x 3 image, the number of paramters doesn't change. Just that convolutions reduces the heightand width of image, so a mobilenet fed with 512 x 512 x 3 images o outputs 16x16x1280 array. i.e. 1280 edges detected of size 16 x 16 pixels. Instead if I feed say 200 x 200 image to it, the only thing that will happen is output of mobilenet will be 8x8x1280 i.e. 1280 edges will be detected by convfilters but the images of those edges will be small i.e. 8x8 instead of 16x16. The total number of edges will remain 1280 in both cases. Even if i feed it 2048 x 2048 x 3 images, mobilenet will output 1280 edges (also called featuremaps) of shape 64x64 pixels each. That's the only difference. Eventually, if i'm gonna do a globalpool over volume, 8x8, 16x16,64x64 all will be reduced to 1 single number or i can do flatten and feed it forward.

#   ----------------------------------------------------------------
#      Without fine-tuning the mobilenet - Using its experience as is
#   -----------------------------------------------------------------

mobilenet_imported = tf.keras.applications.MobileNetV2(
    input_shape = (512,512,3),
    include_top=False,
    weights='imagenet')
for layer in mobilenet_imported.layers:
    layer.trainable = False
layer0 = keras.Input(shape=(512,512,3))
layer1 = RandomFlip('horizontal')(layer0)
layer2 = RandomRotation(0.2)(layer1)
layer3= tf.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input(layer2)
layer4 = mobilenet_imported(layer3)
layer5 = tfl.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(layer4)
layer6 = tfl.Dropout(0.2)(layer5)
layer7 = tfl.Dense(units = 1, activation='sigmoid')(layer6)  # only 1 neuron needed with sigmoid o/p for binary classific
mymodel = keras.Model(inputs = layer0, outputs = layer7)
mymodel.summary()

Observations: Output of mobilenet is 1280 photos of all sorts of edges and each of those photos is 16x16 pixels in size. I think of each convolution filter as an edge detector. So we have 1280 edge detectors. These get fed into the layers I have custom added on top of mobilenet, the first of those being global pool layer. So for each edge detector, we'll have 1 single number. Followed by dropout and last layer has 1 single neuron with sigmoud output for binary classification to use with binary cross entropy loss function

In[18]:
#       -----------------------------------------------------
#           FINE TUNING THE TRANSFER LEARNT MOBILENET MODEL
#
#       Copy paste of above code but with fine-tuning. Leaving some
#       of MobileNet's layers trainable. Freezing 120 layers, remaining 
#       34 of mobilenet are trainable in addition to others i added 

#       The beauty is MobilenetV2 will handle larger images than it 
#       was trained on.So, it was trained on 224 x 224 x 3 but it can 
#       handle 2048 x 2048 x 3 filters. 
#     -----------------------------------------------------

mobilenet_imported = tf.keras.applications.MobileNetV2(input_shape = (512,512,3),include_top=False,weights='imagenet')
for layer in mobilenet_imported.layers[:120]:
    layer.trainable = False
layer0 = keras.Input(shape=(512,512,3))
layer1 = RandomFlip('horizontal')(layer0)
layer2 = RandomRotation(0.2)(layer1)
layer3= tf.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input(layer2)
layer4 = mobilenet_imported(layer3)
layer5 = tfl.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(layer4)
layer6 = tfl.Dropout(0.2)(layer5)
layer7 = tfl.Dense(1,'sigmoid')(layer6)   # for binary classif, only 1 output neuron needed 
model_finetuned = keras.Model(inputs = layer0, outputs = layer7)
model_finetuned.summary()

# Note: Learning rate is slower than before. goal is to learn slowly and not make huge changes to weights, just small
# changes based on my own data

model_finetuned.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=0.0001),
                loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(),
                metrics=['accuracy'])
fine_tune_epochs = 5
total_epochs =  initial_epochs + fine_tune_epochs

model_finetuned.fit(train_dataset,epochs=total_epochs, verbose=2)
print(model_finetuned.evaluate(validation_dataset, verbose=True))

# Observation: training accuracy 99%, test accuracy 92%
# Both accuracies improved by fine-tuning last 30some layers of mobilenet

#  ---------------------------------------------------

import glob
#    this is directory of alpacas
#    sanity check to verify its outputting correct classes

directory = '/Users/namita/Desktop/Python_programs/CNN Course Deep Learning/W2A2/dataset/alpaca/*.jpg'
class_names = train_dataset.class_names
class_0, class_1 = class_names[0], class_names[1]
for filename in glob.glob(directory)[:50]:    
    img = keras.utils.load_img(filename, target_size=(512,512))
    img_array = tf.keras.utils.img_to_array(img)
    img_array = tf.expand_dims(img_array, 0) # Create a batch
    probability= np.round(model_finetuned.predict(img_array).flatten(),2)[0]
    if probability >=0.5: 
        label = class_names[1]
    else: 
        label = class_names[0]
    print((probability,label))
